%I A393153 #29 Apr 08 2026 10:48:50
%S A393153 0,3,4,205,1476,184919,3230816,1437552393,54296530420,91234583767129
%N A393153 Number of social networks of n persons in which the statement "All of my friends have more friends than I have" is true for a majority of the persons.
%C A393153 This refers to the "friendship paradox" which goes back to S. L. Feld's 1991 article claiming that persons have fewer friends than their friends have. In contrast to Feld's results based on averages for numbers of friends and friends' friends, this sequence takes a direct and literally view on Feld's claim, only based on counting. It sets the strictest criterion ("All friends ...") compared with A394695 ("Most friends ...") and A394696 ("Friends on average ...").
%C A393153 The total numbers of social networks as defined by Feld are given by A006129. For n>3, the proportion a(n)/A006129(n) is considerably below 0.5 and does not support Feld's claim. For 7<n<400, simulations suggest that the proportion is decreasing with limit 0. Even n give lower proportions because there appear many ties (statement is true for half of the n persons).
%C A393153 a(n) can be defined in graph theoretic terms. The "network" is a labeled simple graph with n unisolated nodes, n>1.
%C A393153 If d_m(i) = degree of node i in the m-th graph, i = 1,..., n, m = 1,..., A006129(n), d_m(i,j) = degree of j-th node connected with node i, j = 1,..., d_m(i), n_m(i) = #{ j | d_m(i,j) > d_m(i)}, and n_m = #{ i | n_m(i) = d_m(i)}, then a(n) = #{ m | n_m > n/2}.
%H A393153 Scott L. Feld, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2781907">Why Your Friends Have More Friends Than You Do</a>, Am. J. Sociol. 96(6) (1991), p. 1464-1477.
%e A393153 There are 768 networks with 5 nodes (=A006129(5)). 205 of them meet the requirement, making a(5)=205. These can be arranged into 6 classes of graphs with degree vectors
%e A393153    (1,1,1,1,4), 5 labelings,
%e A393153    (1,1,1,2,3), 60 labelings,
%e A393153    (1,1,2,3,3), 60 labelings,
%e A393153    (1,2,2,3,4), 60 labelings,
%e A393153    (2,2,2,3,3), 10 labelings,
%e A393153    (2,2,2,4,4), 10 labelings.
%e A393153  The corresponding graphs are:
%e A393153      o      o           o         o      o---o      o---
%e A393153      |      |          / \       /|\     |  /|     /|\  \
%e A393153    o-o-o    o-o-o    o-o-o-o    o-o-o    | o |    o | o  o
%e A393153      |      |                     |      |/  |     \|/  /
%e A393153      o      o                     o      o---o      o---
%t A393153 nmax = 7; a = {};
%t A393153 Do[an = 0; t = Tuples[{0, 1}, n (n - 1)/2];
%t A393153   Do[v = t[[j]]; m = {ConstantArray[0, n]};
%t A393153     Do[la = Last[NestList[Append[#, 0] &, Take[v, i], n - i]];
%t A393153       m = Join[m, {la}]; v = Drop[v, i], {i, n - 1}];
%t A393153     m = m + Transpose[m]; pr = Product[Total[m[[i]]], {i, n}];
%t A393153     If[pr != 0, di = Table[Total[m[[j]]], {j, n}];
%t A393153       dij = Table[Cases[Table[di[[i]] m[[j]][[i]], {i, n}], Except[0]], {j, n}];
%t A393153       sd = Sign[dij - di];nI = Table[If[Count[sd[[i]], 1] == di[[i]], 1, 0], {i, n}];
%t A393153     If[Total[nI] > n/2, an++]], {j, 2^(n (n - 1)/2)}];
%t A393153   a = Join[a, {an}], {n, 2, nmax}]; a
%Y A393153 Cf. A394695, A394696, A006129
%K A393153 nonn,hard,more,new
%O A393153 2,2
%A A393153 _Manfred Boergens_, Apr 06 2026
%E A393153 a(8)-a(11) from _Bert Dobbelaere_, Apr 08 2026
